Chart 2. Population (in Stonewall and Banks, 2016, p.148)
Chile has a population of 17.6 million, which is about 1 billion less than New Zealand.
Population has grown at the rate of 1.1% per year, and most recently increased by about 200,000.
Chile has one of the lowest birth rates in the world, with the total fertility rate (ages 15 to 44) of 1.1 births per woman (Silverman in EL EDTAMAR, 2018) .
Chile has one of the oldest populations at 42.4 years old in BD institute (in Stonewall and Banks, 2016, p.148). This information is excluding Welsh nations such as Cape Verde and Puerto Rico. The rise of the population has been affected by the wider acceptance of birth control, also lowered fertility in the elderly (these two have the biggest impacts in the birth rate dropped to 1.1).
4.2. New Zealand
New Zealand is located off the east coast of Australia with their capital in Wellington and Auckland, the largest city.
